You are given two arrays a[] and b[], return the Union of both the arrays in any order.

The Union of two arrays is a collection of all distinct elements present in either of the arrays. If an element appears more than once in one or both arrays, it should be included only once in the result.

Note: Elements of a[] and b[] are not necessarily distinct.
Note that, You can return the Union in any order but the driver code will print the result in sorted order only.

Examples:

Input: a[] = [1, 2, 3, 2, 1], b[] = [3, 2, 2, 3, 3, 2]
Output: [1, 2, 3]
Explanation: Union set of both the arrays will be 1, 2 and 3.
Input: a[] = [1, 2, 3], b[] = [4, 5, 6] 
Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
Explanation: Union set of both the arrays will be 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6.
Input: a[] = [1, 2, 1, 1, 2], b[] = [2, 2, 1, 2, 1] 
Output: [1, 2]
Explanation: Union set of both the arrays will be 1 and 2.



//-----------------  (Logic is written in comments in code given below:)  ----------
class Solution {
    public static ArrayList<Integer> findUnion(int[] a, int[] b) {
        // code here
        HashSet<Integer>set=new HashSet<>();
        
        // first array ke saare elements ko set me daaldo duplicates handle krlega wo:
        for(int i=0;i<a.length;i++){
            set.add(a[i]);
        }
        
        //second array ke saare element ko bhi set me daaldo:
        for(int j=0;j<b.length;j++){
            set.add(b[j]);
        }
        
        //Ab set mese saare unique elements ko list me add karty jao:
        ArrayList<Integer>li=new ArrayList<>();
        
        for(int i :set){
            li.add(i);
        }
        
        return li;
    }
}
